The words 571 quocirca astutiae tollmdac sunt caque malitia, quae nult illa quidem videri se csse praudentium are generally regarded as the end ot the first section on false prudence. Yet Cicero would have expressed him· self more distinctly if he had meant to distinguish the examples from one another in this manner 3 at any rate in all cases, where apparent expedi· ency is preferred to virtue, injustice as well as a misconception of true expediency and therefore false prudence shews itself; accordingly they are not easily distinguished from each other. The following examples likewn'se shew a conflict of expediency with justice more than with high mindedness. Still all this does not amount to a reason for pronouncing the words aede praecientia—temperantiae to be an interpolation, as many do. For the words scd quosnam-virtutis inimica could only form the transition to the next division, which is to treat of the conflict between high-mindedness and expediency, on the supposition that virttes=magnitudo aninei. As itis, Cicero never uses virtus in contradistinction to iustitia. Even ifuirtru had this sense here, the point would have been missed: because we derive duties from four kinds of virtue, we shall have to deal with the same four kinds of virtue, when we treat of the condiet between expediency and high-mindedness. Finally, if the first division treated of the conflict be tween apparent prudence and justice, and the second part began only here, Cicero could not say as he does c. 33 restat quarta pars. Heine.
